\b0 A singleton class is one which cannot be instantiated directly but rather has a method for returning the one (and only) instance of the class.\
\

\b Strategy\

\b0 Behaviour of a class is defined by a secondary class, or set of classes, using composition.\
\
e.g. both context and strategy implement the same interface and the context implements it by calling the same method on the strategy and returning the result.\
\

\b Factory\

\b0 A factory class is used to abstract away the complexity of instantiating objects of a \'91family\'92 of classes e.g. a group of classes that all implement a given interface.\
\

\b State\

\b0 A \'91context\'92 class has a tightly coupled \'91state\'92 object (both store references to each other) which represents the current state of the class and has appropriate behaviour.\
